The best American Express credit cards have earned high marks thanks to their stellar rewards and perks. Amex offers a card for almost every type of spender, including credit cards for beginners, casual travelers, road warriors and always-on-the-go business travelers. Whether you’re looking for a no-annual-fee card, global airport lounge access, generous cash back in specific categories or premium access to events, Amex has a card to fit your needs.

Below, check out TPG’s picks for the best Amex cards from our partners to compare and decide which is right for you.

The American Express Platinum Card® has a high annual fee but remains one of the best cards on the market for those who prioritize premium travel experiences. A combination of updated and new statement credits makes the refreshed Amex Platinum an ideal card for frequent travelers and digital entertainment enthusiasts alike.

Pros

  • No foreign transaction fees
  • Up to $600 hotel credit (disbursed as up to $300 in statement credits semiannually; enrollment required)
  • Up to $300 digital entertainment credit (disbursed as up to $25 in statement credits per month; enrollment required)
  • Earns transferable Membership Rewards points

Cons

  • $895 annual fee
  • You may be eligible for as high as 175,000 Membership Rewards® points after you spend $8,000 in eligible purchases on your new Card in your first 6 months of Card Membership. Welcome offers vary and you may not be eligible for an offer. Apply to know if you’re approved and find out your exact welcome offer amount – all with no credit score impact. If you’re approved and choose to accept the Card, your score may be impacted.
  • Get more for your travels with 5X Membership Rewards® points on all flights and prepaid hotel bookings through American Express Travel®, including Fine Hotels + Resorts® and The Hotel Collection bookings. You earn 5X points on flights purchased directly from airlines or through American Express Travel® on up to $500,000 on these purchases per calendar year.
  • More Value! With over 1,550 airport lounges - more than any other credit card company on the market* - enjoy the benefits of the Global Lounge Collection®, over $850 of annual value, with access to Centurion Lounges, 10 complimentary Delta Sky Club® visits when flying on an eligible Delta flight (subject to visit limitations), Priority Pass Select membership (enrollment required), and other select partner lounges. * As of 07/2025.
  • More Value! $200 Uber Cash + $120 Uber One Credit: With the Platinum Card® you can receive $15 in Uber Cash each month plus a bonus $20 in December when you add your Platinum Card® to your Uber account to use on rides and orders in the U.S when you select an Amex Card for your transaction. Plus, when you use the Platinum Card® to pay for an auto-renewing Uber One membership, you can get up to $120 in statement credits each calendar year. Terms apply.
  • More Value! $300 Digital Entertainment Credit: Get up to $25 in statement credits each month after you pay for eligible purchases with the Platinum Card® at participating partners. Enrollment required.
  • More Value! $600 Hotel Credit: Get up to $300 in statement credits semi-annually on prepaid Fine Hotels + Resorts® or The Hotel Collection* bookings through American Express Travel® using the Platinum Card®. *The Hotel Collection requires a minimum two-night stay.
  • New! $400 Resy Credit + Platinum Nights by Resy: When you use the Platinum Card® to pay at U.S. Resy restaurants and to make other eligible purchases through Resy, you can get up to $100 in statement credits each quarter with the $400 Resy Credit benefit. Plus, with Platinum Nights by Resy, you can get special access to reservations on select nights at participating in demand Resy restaurants with the Platinum Card®. Simply add your eligible Card to your Resy profile to book and discover Platinum Nights reservations near you, enrollment required.
  • More Value! $209 CLEAR® Plus Credit: CLEAR® Plus helps get you to your gate faster by using unique facial attributes to verify you are you at 50+ airports nationwide. You can cover the cost of a CLEAR Plus Membership* with up to $209 in statement credits per calendar year after you pay for CLEAR Plus with the Platinum Card®. *Excluding any applicable taxes and fees. Subject to auto-renewal.
  • $200 Airline Fee Credit: Select one qualifying airline and then receive up to $200 in statement credits per calendar year when incidental fees, such as checked bags and in-flight refreshments, are charged by the airline to the Platinum Card® Account*. American Express relies on airlines to submit the correct information on airline transactions to identify incidental fee purchases. If you do not see a credit for a qualifying incidental purchase on your eligible Card after 8 weeks, simply call the number on the back of your Card. Qualifying airlines are subject to change. See terms & conditions for more details.
  • Start your vacation sooner, and keep it going longer. When you book Fine Hotels + Resorts® through American Express Travel®, enjoy noon check-in upon arrival, when available, and guaranteed 4PM check-out.
  • New! $300 lululemon Credit: Enjoy up to $75 in statement credits each quarter when you use the Platinum Card® for eligible purchases at U.S. lululemon retail stores (excluding outlets) and lululemon.com. That’s up to $300 in statement credits each calendar year. Enrollment required.
  • $155 Walmart+ Credit: Receive a statement credit* for one monthly Walmart+ membership (subject to auto-renewal) after you pay for Walmart+ each month with the Platinum Card®. *Up to $12.95 plus applicable local sales tax. Plus Ups not eligible.
  • $100 Saks Credit: Get up to $100 in statement credits annually for purchases at Saks Fifth Avenue or saks.com on the Platinum Card®. That’s up to $50 in statement credits from January through June and up to $50 in statement credits from July through December. No minimum purchase required. Enrollment required.
  • Whenever you need us, we're here. Our Member Services team will ensure you are taken care of. From lost Card replacement to statement questions, we are available to help 24/7.
  • $895 annual fee.

Excellent to Good

This isn’t just a card that’s nice to look at. It packs a real punch, offering 4 points per dollar at restaurants worldwide (on the first $50,000 in purchases per calendar year; then 1 point per dollar) and U.S. supermarkets (on the first $25,000 in purchases per calendar year; then 1 point per dollar). There’s also an up to $120 annual dining credit at Grubhub, The Cheesecake Factory, Goldbelly, Wine.com, and Five Guys, plus it added an up to $120 annually ($10 per month) in Uber Cash, which can be used on Uber Eats orders or Uber rides in the U.S. The card must be added to your Uber account and you can redeem with any Amex card. All this make it a very strong contender for all food purchases, which has become a popular spending category. Enrollment required for select benefits. Read our full review of the American Express Gold Card.

Pros

  • 4 points per dollar on dining at restaurants worldwide (on the first $50,000 in purchases per calendar year; then 1 point per dollar) and U.S. supermarkets (on the first $25,000 in purchases per calendar year; then 1 point per dollar)
  • 3 points per dollar on flights booked directly with the airline or with Amex Travel

Cons

  • Weak on travel and everyday spending bonus categories
  • Not as effective for those living outside the U.S.
  • Some may have trouble using Uber/food credits; few travel perks and protections
  • You may be eligible for as high as 100,000 Membership Rewards® Points after you spend $6,000 in eligible purchases on your new Card in your first 6 months of Card Membership. Welcome offers vary and you may not be eligible for an offer. Apply to know if you’re approved and find out your exact welcome offer amount – all with no credit score impact. If you’re approved and choose to accept the Card, your score may be impacted.

  • Earn 4X Membership Rewards® points per dollar spent at US supermarkets, on up to $25,000 in purchases per calendar year, then 1X points for the rest of the year.
  • Earn 3X Membership Rewards® points per dollar spent on flights booked directly with airlines or on AmexTravel.com.
  • Earn 2X Membership Rewards® points per dollar spent on prepaid hotels and other eligible purchases booked on AmexTravel.com.
  • Earn 1X Membership Rewards® point per dollar spent on all other eligible purchases.
  • $120 Uber Cash on Gold: Add your Gold Card to your Uber account and get $10 in Uber Cash each month to use on orders and rides in the U.S. when you select an American Express Card for your transaction. That’s up to $120 Uber Cash annually. Plus, after using your Uber Cash, use your Card to earn 4X Membership Rewards® points for Uber Eats purchases made with restaurants or U.S. supermarkets. Point caps and terms apply.

American Express Platinum Card®

The American Express Platinum Card® is a great travel companion thanks to perks like no foreign transaction fees and enhancements like a generous up to $600 hotel credit (disbursed as up to $300 in statement credits biannually). Now, it also features more lifestyle credits that cardmembers can take advantage of to help offset its hefty annual fee. Enrollment required.

Frequent travelers and digital entertainment subscribers will enjoy travel perks like lounge access and an up to $209 Clear Plus statement credit in addition to an up to $300 digital entertainment credit (disbursed as up to $25 per month in statement credits). Enrollment may be required and you may be subject to auto-renewal.

Adding this card to your rotation makes sense if you can use its perks and statement credits to offset its $895 annual fee.

If you want a premium travel and lifestyle card that’s not nearly $900, consider the Chase Sapphire Reserve®. It features a $795 annual fee — which is still a big figure — but offers several similar perks and credits that offset this fee, and it earns transferable Ultimate Rewards points, one of the most valuable reward currencies on the market.

The Business Platinum Card® from American Express

Business owners get to take advantage of solid travel perks but also business-specific perks such as an up to $120 wireless telephone service statement credit (up to $10 per month) for wireless telephone service purchases made directly with a wireless provider in the U.S. Enrollment required.

Business travelers who can take advantage of this card’s statement credits and would benefit from perks like lounge access and hotel elite status.

If you’re often on the go for work trips, this Amex Business Platinum card is a solid choice. It’s packed with travel-related statement credits and benefits in addition to offering business-specific perks that are pretty straightforward to use.

 If you’re in the market for a premium business card but don’t want to commit to the Amex Business Platinum, consider the Chase Sapphire Reserve for Business℠. Like its consumer counterpart, the Sapphire Reserve for Business earns valuable Ultimate Rewards points and also offers business-related statement credits and perks.

American Express® Gold Card

The Amex Gold awards 4 points per dollar at U.S. supermarkets (on up to $25,000 in spending each year, then 1 point) and 4 points per dollar at worldwide restaurants (on the first $50,000 in purchases per calendar year; then 1 point per dollar), making it one of the more rewarding cards for everyday purchases.

Anyone who’s looking to maximize their grocery and dining purchases can get a ton of value from the Amex Gold.

“There's no better card for groceries and dining than the Amex Gold. I earn 4 points per dollar in both of these categories, and with additional perks like monthly statement credits and the ability to transfer my Membership Rewards points to valuable airline partners, the card is a mainstay in my wallet.” — Nick Ewen, director of content

For a much lower annual cost, consider the Chase Sapphire Preferred® Card, which offers 5 points per dollar on purchases through Chase Travel℠; 3 points per dollar on dining, select streaming services and online grocery delivery (excluding Walmart, Target and wholesale clubs); and 2 points per dollar on all other travel purchases.

American Express® Business Gold Card

Membership Rewards points are incredibly valuable, and the Amex Business Gold card lets small businesses earn a ton of them. You’ll earn 4 points per dollar on the two categories where you spend the most each billing cycle (on up to $150,000 in combined purchases each year, then 1 point per dollar). These points can go a long way toward your next luxury flight redemption.

Any small-business owner with significant spending in the eligible bonus categories — which include U.S. gas stations, U.S. restaurants, select technology providers and certain advertising purchases — can get great value from the Amex Business Gold card.

“No other card provides the earning potential and adaptability this card has. Sure, its $375 annual fee isn’t cheap, but I love the fact I don’t need to think about what purchases I put on this card. It will automatically adapt and provide 4 points per dollar in my top two spending categories each billing cycle.” — Ryan Smith, former credit cards writer

For a fixed earning rate and no annual fee (see rates and fees), go for the The Blue Business® Plus Credit Card from American Express. You’ll earn 2 Membership Rewards points per dollar spent on all purchases (on up to $50,000 in spending each calendar year, then 1 point per dollar).

Blue Cash Preferred® Card from American Express

The Blue Cash Preferred offers solid cash-back rewards across a variety of categories, but you can also enjoy a lucrative welcome offer and additional statement credits for select purchases during the year.

Someone who doesn’t want to worry about maximizing travel rewards is a great fit for the Blue Cash Preferred.

“The Blue Cash Preferred Card is the card I recommended to my parents when they were looking for a new cash-back rewards card for their groceries. My parents prefer the simplicity of cash-back rewards and I knew they'd benefit from earning 6% cash back on up to $6,000 per year in purchases at U.S. supermarkets, then 1% after. Compared to the 1.5% cash back they were earning on these purchases, the elevated earnings easily justified adding the Blue Cash Preferred to their wallet.” — Katie Genter, senior writer

Cash back is received in the form of Reward Dollars that can be redeemed as a statement credit and at Amazon.com checkout.

For similar perks at a lower cost, consider the Blue Cash Everyday® Card from American Express, which has comparable cash-back rates for no annual fee (see rates and fees).

Delta SkyMiles® Gold American Express Card

There’s a lot to love about the Delta SkyMiles Gold Amex, thanks to perks like no foreign transaction fees, a free checked bag, priority boarding and a $200 Delta flight credit after you spend $10,000 or more on your card in a calendar year. It has an annual fee of just $150, $0 intro annual fee for your first year.

You’ll enjoy great airline-specific perks and travel benefits with a low annual fee, making the Delta Gold Amex a great option for casual Delta flyers and new travelers.

“As someone who likes flying Delta but doesn’t fly often enough to earn elite status, my Delta SkyMiles Gold Amex still gives me elitelike perks to help upgrade my travel experience.” — Madison Blancaflor, senior content operations editor

Those seeking Delta Medallion elite status may prefer the Delta SkyMiles® Platinum American Express Card. This card can help you requalify for Medallion status based on your spending each year and also includes additional perks for frequent Delta travelers.

The Blue Business® Plus Credit Card from American Express

It’s rare that a card with no annual fee awards fully transferable points, but that’s exactly what you’ll get with the Blue Business Plus. These points can be redeemed for travel directly with American Express, but for more value, you can transfer them to an eligible hotel or airline loyalty program.

Small-business owners who don’t want to worry about maximizing bonus categories can earn a ton of Amex points with the Blue Business Plus.

“There are very few no-annual-fee cards that award fully transferable points, but the Amex Blue Business Plus is one of them. Not only that, you'll earn 2 Membership Rewards points for every dollar you spend (on up to $50,000 each year, then 1 point). That's a fantastic return of 4% back based on TPG's valuations, making this a great option for your small-business needs.” — Nick Ewen, director of content

If you don’t want to worry about travel rewards and instead want to plow your earnings back into your small business, go for the American Express Blue Business Cash™ Card — which also incurs no annual fee (see rates and fees) and gives 2% cash back on every purchase (on up to $50,000 in spending each calendar year, then 1% cash back). These rewards are automatically applied to your card balance as a statement credit.

Blue Cash Everyday® Card from American Express

For no annual fee, you’ll enjoy up to 3% cash back on a variety of purchases. Cash Back is received in the form of Reward Dollars that can be redeemed as a statement credit and at Amazon.com checkout.

Those looking for lucrative cash-back rates without an annual fee are great candidates for the Blue Cash Everyday.

“I added this card to my wallet shortly after my first travel card as a way to earn better rewards on U.S. gas and U.S. supermarket purchases. Three percent back on both categories (up to $6,000 per year in purchases, then one percent after) was a great way for me to earn higher cash back on many of my everyday purchases without any added annual fee.” — Jack Markham, senior director

Cash back is received in the form of Reward Dollars that can be redeemed as a statement credit and at Amazon.com checkout.

The Blue Cash Preferred® Card from American Express offers notably higher cash-back rates at select merchants, so depending on your spending habits, you could come out ahead — even once the card’s $95 annual fee kicks in, $0 intro annual fee for the first year (see rates and fees).

Delta SkyMiles® Reserve American Express Card

The Delta SkyMiles Reserve provides cardholders with complimentary Sky Club access whenever they fly with Delta Airlines in addition to complimentary Centurion Lounge access as well. 

Reserve Card Members receive 15 Visits per year to the Delta Sky Club; to earn an unlimited number of Visits each year, the total eligible purchases on the Card must equal $75,000 or more each calendar year.

Frequent Delta flyers who book travel and make purchases directly with the airline should carry this card in their wallets since it earns 3 miles per dollar spent in this category. Plus, with the SkyMiles Reserve card, your first checked bag is free on Delta flights.

If you enjoy complimentary upgrades, the Delta SkyMiles Reserve card can help you access them. Even if you haven’t achieved Medallion status yet, this credit card adds you to the complimentary upgrade list (after Medallion-status members). You’ll also get a 20% statement credit on eligible inflight purchases when you use your SkyMiles Reserve card.

The Delta SkyMiles® Platinum American Express Card features a lower annual fee of $350 (see rates and fees) and still offers cardholders plenty of perks, including a $120 Global Entry statement credit every four years and 15% savings when using miles to book award travel on Delta flights booked through the airline.

Hilton Honors American Express Aspire Card

Exceptional hotel perks, including Hilton Diamond status, an annual Free Night Reward and generous travel credits.

Travelers who frequently stay at Hilton hotels and want luxury-level benefits without elite-qualifying stays.

The combination of high-value credits, elite status and premium travel benefits can far outweigh the $550 annual fee if you maximize them.

For Marriott loyalists, the Marriott Bonvoy Brilliant® American Express® Card delivers premium hotel perks within the Marriott portfolio, including an annual free night award and automatic Platinum Elite status, with a slightly higher annual fee. The World of Hyatt Credit Card is ideal for Hyatt loyalists, providing solid value through free nights, elite status and bonus points on Hyatt stays. For a mid-tier option within the same hotel family, the Hilton Honors American Express Surpass® Card provides valuable Hilton perks at a more moderate annual fee.

American Express® Green Card

The Green Card is one of several offerings from American Express and is well-suited for those who want a travel card without the hefty annual fees of more premium products.

The information for the American Express Green Card has been collected independently by The Points Guy. The card details on this page have not been reviewed or provided by the card issuer.

This card offers solid earning rates in popular spend categories and is ideal for travelers who want to earn transferable Amex Membership Rewards points.

Whether you’re already in the Amex ecosystem or a newbie to it, the Green Card is an easy way to transition into earning Membership Rewards points, taking advantage of Amex Offers and generally getting acquainted with this issuer.

If you want a more premium product, consider the American Express Platinum Card®. In addition to earning a large stash of Membership Rewards points, you’ll get access to Centurion Lounges as well as purchase protections like extended warranties**.

Here’s why American Express remains a fan-favorite issuer

Thanks to the myriad perks of being an Amex cardholder, the issuer has been able to offer a product suitable for every type of spender. 

Amex cards are so popular that 39% of TPG readers we surveyed shared that they simultaneously hold both the American Express Platinum Card® and the American Express® Gold Card.

Cardholders who are frequent travelers, prefer staying at a specific hotel chain or are loyal to a specific airline get to choose from several cobranded Amex products while those who prefer to earn straightforward cash back or points also have lots of great options to consider.

Amex card rewards include on-property credits at select hotels, travel credits when you book and pay for a flight with certain Amex cards and even dining credits at specific restaurants and on eligible takeout and delivery orders. Both the Amex Gold and Amex Platinum cards are great for foodies and travelers alike — and make an especially powerful combo for foodies who frequently fly, too!

This information was collected via opt-in surveys of TPG’s roughly 900,000 daily newsletter subscribers in May-June 2024. All data is anonymous and aggregated; you can view our full methodology for collecting and utilizing data here.

How to choose the best Amex credit card

The best Amex credit card for you depends on what you want your card to do; are you looking to earn cash back? Do you want transferable reward points? At TPG, we recommend choosing a card that matches your spending habits, including earning rewards in your top spending categories.
Here are some of the main points to consider when choosing an Amex credit card:
  • 1
    Welcome bonus
    Go with an Amex that features a decent Welcome bonus — you can use the reward you earn for future travel plans or to pay down a balance if you opt for a cash-back card. Select an option that has an achievable spend threshold and that you’ll earn the currency most valuable to you — whether it’s points, miles or cash back.
  • 2
    Annual fee
    While some of the Amex cards on our list feature high annual fees, they also offer stellar travel and shopping protections in addition to other benefits like credits in certain categories. We also included no annual fee cards for those who don’t want to worry about paying for a card each year.
  • 3
    Bonus categories
    The best Amex cards on this list feature several bonus categories, ensuring there’s a good fit for every type of consumer. If you want to earn rewards on grocery store purchases or flights booked through the Amex travel portal, it’s likely that one of our top-rated picks is well-suited to your specific needs.

Pros + cons of American Express cards

Pros

  • American Express cards can earn points, miles or cash back on every dollar you spend, helping you maximize your reward-earning strategy
  • Many American Express cards offer valuable shopping and travel protections
  • Select American Express cards provide perks like statement credits, elite status and more

Cons

  • The cost of borrowing on Amex cards is higher than traditional loans
  • American Express may not be accepted by all merchants
  • American Express typically only allows you to earn one welcome bonus per card once in your lifetime

American Express benefits

American Express cards have long held a reputation for lucrative benefits, though the extent of these perks depends on the card you have.

Frequently asked questions

Yes, American Express is a reliable issuer that offers a variety of lucrative cards. This includes a number of great cash-back options as well as many that award Membership Rewards points, which are some of the most valuable transferable points out there.

To start an American Express application, you can click on any of the links in this guide and follow the onscreen prompts. Be prepared with your Social Security number along with all of your contact information.

No, but the issuer has made strides in recent years. In fact, according to the February 2023 Nilson report, Amex is now accepted at 99% of U.S. merchants that take credit cards — putting it nearly even with networks like Visa and Mastercard.

There’s no single threshold to get approved for an American Express card, but most of them require good or excellent credit. However, even that may not be enough for a premium card like the the American Express Platinum Card®.

Amex generally limits the number of personal cards you can have to five, though cards without preset spending limits* — like the American Express Platinum Card® and American Express® Gold Card — are typically excluded from this number, as are small-business Amex cards.

However, that’s not a license to apply for new cards with abandon, since American Express will consider your history of opening and closing accounts when deciding on your approval. You can read more information in the Amex section of our guide to credit card application restrictions.

*The amount you can spend adapts based on factors such as your purchase, payment and credit history.

There’s no one “best” American Express card for everyone. If you’re looking for more luxury when traveling, the American Express Platinum Card® could be a great fit. However, if you just want simple cash-back rewards, you may prefer a product like the Blue Cash Preferred® Card from American Express.

Start by identifying the type of rewards you want — Membership Rewards points, airline miles, hotel points or cash back. Next, consider the types of purchases you make on a regular basis along with other benefits you value highly. Then, pick the card that offers your preferred rewards currency along with sufficiently lucrative benefits and earning rates based on your typical spending habits.
